\subsection{Radar Cross Section (RCS)}\label{LR_RCS}\index{Radar Cross Section (RCS)}
%In the radiation/scattering problems where electrically large structures are involved, efficient solution is provided by, the Geometrical Theory of Diffraction (GTD), Uniform Theory of Diffraction (UTD) or Uniform Asymptotic Theory of Diffraction (UAT). Due to the local nature of diffraction at high frequencies, GTD analysis can be developed by, simulating these structures with components having shapes that locally provide a sufficiently accurate representation of the dominant reflection and diffraction effects. The analysis of complex scatterer is usually carried out by breaking the problem into simpler problems involvin canonical structures like half-plane, cone, corner etc.% which are detailed in \cite{Pathak_utd}, \cite{Sikta_F_corner_diffraction}, \cite{Burnside_tip_diffraction}. 




 %The analysis of complex scatterer is usually carried out by breaking the problem into simpler problems involving structures like half-plane, wedge, finite cylinders, finite cone, corner etc. Electromagnetic scattering from canonical objects like half-plane, cone, corner etc are initially studied and available in \cite{Pathak_utd}, \cite{Sikta_F_corner_diffraction}, \cite{Burnside_tip_diffraction}. 


Application of geometrical theory of diffraction (GTD) to predict the radar cross section (RCS) accordingly has been the subject of interest for quite some time. The problem of mono-static scattering by a finite half-plate has earlier been formulated by Ross \cite{Ross_RCS_rectangular_flat_plates} using GTD. Ross\rq s GTD formulation gave better results than the physical optics (PO) approach. However, as a consequence of the defect is the Keller\rq s theory \cite{Keller_gtd}, Ross\rq approach predicted infinite field at the boundary. In this paper we have used uniform theory of diffraction (UTD) \cite{Pathak_utd}. The results thus obtained have been compared with those of Ross\rq.

The equivalent current format has been used as a basis for finding diffraction coefficients for a corner \cite{Sikta_F_corner_diffraction}. This solution was originally developed to evaluate the fields diffracted by a comer for the case of a monopole mounted on a finite flat plate. The remaining task in this paper is to compute RCS of Sikta\rq s triangle \cite{Brinkley_UTD_Higher_Order_Terms}. The field scattered by Sikta\rq s triangle constructed by summing the contributions from each individual corner \cite{Sikta_F_corner_diffraction}, \cite{Burnside_tip_diffraction} and half-plane \cite{Pathak_utd}. The computed RCS of Sikta\rq s triangle are compared with the results given by Sikta and Marhefka in \cite{Brinkley_UTD_Higher_Order_Terms}. Sikta calculated the fields using Ryan and Peters equivalent currents to find the first order terms plus higher order terms (double and triple diffraction) where as, Marhefka used corner diffraction coefficient detailed in \cite{Brinkley_UTD_Higher_Order_Terms}.

